      #generalinvestor
        h4 General Investor Questions
        #accordion2.panel-group
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_1")
                | What is investing in businesses about?
            |         
            #2_1.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Investing in businesses is about picking businesses that you believe have the potential to grow. You invest in exchange for a portion of their equity, meaning that you buy shares in the business. If a business you've invested in succeeds, the shares that you own will become worth more than you paid for them. However, if the business fails - as the majority of early-stage businesses do - you'll lose your investment. It is therefore very important that everyone does a deep thinking before deciding to invest in companies.
          |     
          |     
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_2")
                | Can investing in businesses be profitable?
            |         
            #2_2.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | It depends. Statistics show that angel investing can be profitable if you diversify your investments across promising startups. Though no angel investment can assure sure shot returns, studies have shown that wise decisions taken over the merit of the idea, team and execution can often beat returns from traditional investment sources in the market.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_3")
                | I get that investing in early stage businesses can be very risky, why should I still do it?
            |         
            #2_3.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | We at FundMyVenture try to see it this way - no pain, no gain. Its true that most businesses fail early, but still a small chunk (statistically speaking) are able to bear the heat of the market. Investments made in such companies can often return many times the original investment you made. In a nutshell, if you have full faith in the business along with the team and their vision for the company, you should invest in it.
          |     
          |     
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_4")
                | Will investing in businesses continue to be as profitable in the future?
            |         
            #2_4.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | No one can say for sure, but we predict that it will become even more profitable, especially relative to other traditional forms of investment (like mutual funds, stocks, bank deposit,  bonds, debentures, etc). In a world where the creation of value is increasingly driven by innovation and adaptability rather than scale, businesses that are small and agile are well-positioned to outperform their bigger, slower counterparts. There will continue to be many failures of course, but we think that there will be more, and larger, successes, which in turn will mean that increasingly outsized returns will be available to investors in early-stage companies.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_5")
                | Why do businesses need to raise investment?
            |         
            #2_5.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | When an entrepreneur starts a new venture, they usually need money to turn the idea into the beginnings of an actual business that can reach out to customers and later-stage investors. Depending on the business, this capital might allow them to build a minimum viable product (technology startups), buy equipment (manufacturing businesses), lease space and acquire inventory (retail companies), hire a great team, expand their market and customer acquisition efforts, and so forth.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_6")
                | How much equity do investors get for their investment?
            |         
            #2_6.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Each business decides how much money it wants to raise in exchange for a certain percentage of its equity, and each investor’s equity interest will be proportionate to the size of their investment. So if a campaign raises Rs. 10,50,000 in exchange for 20% of its equity, and you invest Rs. 10,500 (1% of Rs. 10,50,000), you will receive 0.20% (1% of 20%) of the equity of the business.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_0")
                | I have no idea about investing in businesses. I am a complete noob at it. How can I possibly invest in businesses.
            |         
            #2_0.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Don't worry. We understand your concern. We try our best to connect the companies raising funds on FundMyVenture to first raise a substantial percentage of their fundraise from seasoned angels and other agencies (angel groups, early stage investment funds) so that the deals you see on FundMyVenture are vetted by people who already know the process and analysis that goes behind investing in startups.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_7")
                | Is FundMyVenture an angel network?
            |         
            #2_7.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | No. Angel networks introduce investors and entrepreneurs but tend not to get closely involved in the investment process - it’s up to each investor and each entrepreneur to negotiate a deal individually and get lawyers to draft up the necessary contracts. FundMyVenture is a full investment platform, allowing investors to invest in businesses directly. It is upto the investor and the startup's discretion whether they want to take up the legal work by themselves or with our partner legal team. Many angels choose to invest through FundMyVenture because of the increased efficiency and access to deal flow.
          |      
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_need")
                | Why do people need FundMyVenture to be able to invest?
            |         
            #2_need.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Unless they're extremely wealthy and have lots of time on their hands, it is very difficult for most people to invest in early-stage businesses the traditional way as a business angel. Due to transaction costs and other considerations, most angels find they need to invest at least Rs. 2,00,000 per business; and because this is a high-risk type of investing, many angels try to invest in at least 10 companies and often more. This means that to be an angel, people generally need to have Rs. 20,00,000 or more to allocate just to businesses (which means that they need to have far more than Rs. 20,00,000 in order to build a diversified portfolio that includes safer assets), and they also need to have the time to find, negotiate and execute a large number of offline investments.
                br
                |  Investors with that much money and time available might not need FundMyVenture (although we can still provide them with access to investment opportunities they might not otherwise find, and more efficient investing). For everyone else, though, FundMyVenture provides the chance to invest small amounts of money through a streamlined, online process, which means that we're the one way to participate in the benefits of investing in early-stage businesses without having both a fortune and tons of time to spare.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_8")
                | Is FundMyVenture like peer-to-peer lending?
            |         
            #2_8.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | There are similarities but also important differences. The concept of having many people provide finance in small quantities via the internet was pioneered by peer-to-peer lending platforms.    However, there are two major distinctions between peer-to-peer lending and FundMyVenture. First, FundMyVenture is generally about early and growth-stage finance for businesses, whereas most peer-to-peer lending sites focus on personal finance or later-stage businesses. And second, FundMyVenture is about equity investment rather than debt, which means that investors who use FundMyVenture can achieve much higher returns than they would in peer-to-peer lending, but they also bear the risks of the business and won't get their original investment back if the business fails.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_9")
                | Is FundMyVenture a form of crowdfunding?
            |         
            #2_9.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Yes. Crowdfunding is a broad term that has come to be used for a wide-range of financing techniques, including charitable and political donations, art patronage and entrepreneurial finance. Most forms of crowdfunding have not provided funders with a potential for financial return: they usually rely on altruistic giving or non-monetary rewards (donation and reward based crowdfunding). FundMyVenture allows people to back businesses by crowd investing, rather than donating, and therefore receive genuine financial returns when their investments are successful.
                br
                |                 An important example here is that of Oculus Rift. While Oculus raised initial money (to realize the market value proposition) via reward based crowdfunding website Kickstarter, none of the people who backed the project then on Kickstarter got any return when Oculus Rift was acquired by Facebook for $2 Billion!
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_10")
                | Is there a chance investors could lose more than they invested?
            |         
            #2_10.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | No. As an equity investor, investor liability will be limited to the amount invested, which means that even though they might not get their investment back, they can't be called on to pay anything more no matter what happens to the business.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_11")
                | What are the main risks of investing?
            |         
            #2_11.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | There are three key risks when investing in early-stage and growth-focused companies. 
                br
                | The business could fail, and investors won't get any money back. 
                |                 
                br
                | Even if the business succeeds, investments are likely to be illiquid for a substantial period of time - often a number of years - meaning that investors are unlikely to be able to sell the investment and will likely not receive dividends from it either. 
                |                 
                br
                | There is the risk of dilution: if the startup raises more capital later on (which most successful businesses need to do), the percentage of equity that existing investors hold in it will decrease relative to what they originally had.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_12")
                | Should anyone invest all of their money in businesses?
            |         
            #2_12.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Absolutely not. We strongly suggest that investors invest most of their capital in safer, more liquid assets, such as mutual funds, bonds and bank deposits. As a rule of thumb, active angel investors tend to invest no more than between 5% and 15% of their capital in early-stage businesses. Whatever proportion of money users choose to invest, the 
                b most important thing is that they can afford to lose all of it
                | .
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_13")
                | Should users invest money in one business or small amounts in multiple businesses?
            |         
            #2_13.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | We think that the better practice is to diversify by investing small amounts in multiple businesses. Because the distribution of returns from early – stage businesses is highly skewed - meaning that the majority of startups fail, and most of the profits come from a few big successes - investors are more likely to make a profit by investing in a number of businesses in the hopes that the successes of a few outweigh the losses of the rest.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_14")
                | Who can invest on FundMyVenture?
            |         
            #2_14.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | People from around the world may invest through FundMyVenture. While government of India imposed strong regulations on funding coming from outside India, rules are getting formalized day by day. For Indian nationals, funding in startups is not a highly regulated activity and can be done if one sticks to the guidelines prescribed by the Government of India (don't worry, we are here to help and notify you of the restrictions imposed, if any). 
                br
                | Please contact reachout@fundmyventure.co for further details.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_15")
                | Does FundMyVenture review each campaign's Q&A section?
            |         
            #2_15.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | We do not review or approve the content in the Q&A which accompanies FundMyVenture campaigns. The Q&A constitutes "one-off communications" between entrepreneurs and potential investors and should be treated as one-on-one conversations. It is the responsibility of a campaigning entrepreneur to monitor and respond to questions raised in their Q&A and respond to them accordingly. We are not able to remove Q&A content on request, however, we do reserve the right to remove any content in the Q&A that we consider spam, abuse or trolling.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_16")
                | Does FundMyVenture advise as to where to invest?
            |         
            #2_16.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | We are not authorised to give advice. While we confirm and approve all the information provided in each campaign, we do not make our own judgment about whether it's a good business. We believe that a large number of diverse investors are better suited to assess the business’s prospects than a few professional managers. That said, we do our best to exclude businesses that are proposing to do something illegal, unethical or just not viable.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_17")
                | Is there a minimum or a maximum investment?
            |         
            #2_17.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | It depends. Government of India imposes a restriction that a company can raise money from a maximum of 200 investors in one financial year. As a result, it is often possible that there is a minimum investment an individual needs to make to ensure that they get their name in the shareholder's certificate. For example: A company trying to raise 1 crore in their fundraise cannot simply afford to include every investor's name in the share holder's certificate if their investment is say less than Rs. 10,000. The maximum investment is however much money the business is willing to accept, less anything that's already been committed by other investors.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_18")
                | How do I pay for an investment?
            |         
            #2_18.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Currently, we allow only bank transfers as the medium of exchange for the transaction. We do not charge any fees for paying for investments or depositing funds in your Investment Account. However, you will be responsible for any fees charged by your bank when making a bank transfer.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_19")
                | Why can't I pay with 3rd party payment gateway solutions?
            |         
            #2_19.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | We understand your concern. We are working on tying up with payment processing companies like Paytm/CC Avenue to assure easy transfers. But there are certain issues associated with such transactions. Typically, payment processing companies take up atleast 2% cut out of the total transaction. This translates to a huge amount when the transaction size is high (Rs. 1000 for every investment of Rs. 50,000).
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_20")
                | What happens if a fundraise doesn’t reach its target?
            |         
            #2_20.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Investors will get their money back in full. FundMyVenture operates on an all-or-nothing basis, meaning that if the business does not raise all of the money its campaign is seeking within it's allotted campaign period, it gets nothing and investors receive their funds back into their account.
                br
                |                 If however, say the fundraise is stuck very close to completion (greater than 90% of the initial ask), then it is upto the individual investor and the startup if they want to continue with the transaction. A benchmark of 90% is generally kept so that the entrepreneur gets enough money to deliver what they promised off in the first place (during the fund raise).
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_21")
                | What is "overfunding" of fundraise campaigns?
            |         
            #2_21.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | After a fundraise has reached 100% of its funding target, entrepreneurs have the option of raising more than their target investment amount if the demand is there from investors. We call this "overfunding". 
                br
                |  We operate an all-or-nothing model where entrepreneurs must reach their minimum target or investors get their funds back. But if a fundraise goes into overfunding, the entrepreneur will be able to accept any amount from 100% and up during the remaining duration of their fundraise (in exchange for a corresponding amount of additional equity). Entrepreneurs are not required to take investment but reserve the right to accept any amount beyond 100%.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_22")
                | Once a fundraise has reached its target will the investment definitely be completed?
            |         
            #2_22.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | No. Once all the money has been invested, we conduct a legal due diligence process and negotiate a legal agreement with the business on behalf of investors before the investment is completed. If we identify problems in the legal due diligence process or are unable to agree legal terms, we'll cancel the investment and return funds back to investors, just as we would if the fundraise had not received commitments for all of the money it was seeking.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_23")
                | Are investments public?
            |         
            #2_23.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Investors can choose to make each investment public or anonymous at the time of investment.
                | Even if an investment is private, the business will be informed of the identity of all of their investors before the investment is completed, and in certain cases investments may be recorded in public filings or elsewhere as required by law.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_24")
                | Can I withdraw my funds?
            |         
            #2_24.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | If you’ve transferred money into your account and not yet invested it, or if money has been refunded or paid to your account you can withdraw the money at time. However, once the deal is done, it is typically not possible for the investor to withdraw the invested amount.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_25")
                | What are the eligibility requirements in order to make investments through FundMyVenture?
            |         
            #2_25.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | To make investments, you need to self-certify as a "high net worth individual" or a "sophisticated investor" (or, if you are an institution, a “high net worth company, unincorporated association, etc”). This is necessary to show us that that you have the professional judgment and understanding to appreciate the risks and considerations of investing in early-stage businesses as an asset class.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#2_26")
                | What do users get for their investment?
