            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#3_8")
                | Is FundMyVenture like peer-to-peer lending?
            |         
            #3_8.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | There are similarities but also important differences. The concept of having many people provide finance in small quantities via the internet was pioneered by peer-to-peer lending platforms.    However, there are two major distinctions between peer-to-peer lending and FundMyVenture. First, FundMyVenture is generally about early and growth-stage finance for businesses, whereas most peer-to-peer lending sites focus on personal finance or later-stage businesses. And second, FundMyVenture is about equity investment rather than debt, which means that investors who use FundMyVenture can achieve much higher returns than they would in peer-to-peer lending, but they also bear the risks of the business and won't get their original investment back if the business fails.
          |     
          .panel.panel-default
            .panel-heading
              h4.panel-title(data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#3_9")
                | Is FundMyVenture a form of crowdfunding?
            |         
            #3_9.panel-collapse.collapse
              .panel-body
                | Yes. Crowdfunding is a broad term that has come to be used for a wide-range of financing techniques, including charitable and political donations, art patronage and entrepreneurial finance. Most forms of crowdfunding have not provided funders with a potential for financial return: they usually rely on altruistic giving or non-monetary rewards (donation and reward based crowdfunding). FundMyVenture allows people to back businesses by crowd investing, rather than donating, and therefore receive genuine financial returns when their investments are successful.
                br
                |                 An important example here is that of Oculus Rift. While Oculus raised initial money (to realize the market value proposition) via reward based crowdfunding website Kickstarter, none of the people who backed the project then on Kickstarter got any return when Oculus Rift was acquired by Facebook for $2 Billion!
